article.headline: Carter scores just four points in victory
article.linkText: Murray picks up Vince's slack, spurs Raptors
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- With Vince Carter playing the worst basketball of his career, Lamond Murray picked up the slack. Murray scored all 13 of his points in the fourth quarter, helping the Toronto Raptors overcome a 20-point deficit in the second half to beat the San Antonio Spurs 96-91 Sunday. Carter scored just four points on 2-for-9 shooting and didn't play in the fourth quarter, dropping his scoring average to a career-low 14.5 points. "There's no sense in sitting there and pouting," said Carter, who wants to be traded. "It wasn't my day. I couldn't buy a basket." Carter has been benched in the fourth quarter of three games this season because Toronto's reserves have played better. Behind Murray's 6-for-7 shooting, the Raptors overcame a 19-point deficit in the fourth quarter -- the largest fourth-quarter comeback in team history. "Wow, that's crazy," Murray said. Murray spent most of last season on the sideline, but he's been playing well under new coach Sam Mitchell. "This is a new year. You put everything behind you. I've been in the league long enough to know you have good years and bad years," Murray said. Rafer Alston had 20 points, a season-high 11 assists and seven rebounds for the Raptors, who ended a five-game losing streak. Toronto ended San Antonio's six-game winning streak by outscoring them 33-9 in the final period. The Spurs tied a franchise low with two field goals in the fourth. "Obviously, we cashed it in and played like the game was over," San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said Tim Duncan had 26 points and 15 rebounds, but just three points in the fourth. "I'll put this loss on my shoulders," Duncan said. "I missed a bunch of layups and free throws, chances and opportunities to go up six or eight points." Malik Rose's three-point play and dunk late in the third quarter gave San Antonio a 20-point lead. But the Spurs scored just two points in the first 6:04 of the fourth, going 0-for-8 from the field and 2-for-8 from the line. Murray scored eight points as Toronto started the fourth on a 16-2 run, cutting the lead to five. After Alston made consecutive driving layups to give Toronto a 89-88 lead with 2:53 left, Robert Horry made a jumper to regain the lead for San Antonio. But Murray, with Horry in his face, followed with a 3-pointer to make it 92-90 with 1:29 left. Murray blocked Duncan's dunk attempt, and Duncan missed a hook shot. Murray followed with a 19-foot jumper, and Alston's two free throws made it 96-91 with 8.8 seconds left. Toronto's Chris Bosh added 20 points and 10 rebounds. "This is a confidence booster, a momentum booster, an everything kinda of booster," Bosh said. "Anything you want to call it, it was just that. We needed it."

Game notes
Duncan was listening to his iPod during the 20-minute warmup before the game. On Tuesday, Carter was informed by the NBA that he couldn't listen to his because it violated the league's rules on proper attire. Carter told a reporter what Duncan was doing. ... The game had the same officiating crew that worked at Friday night's Pacers-Pistons brawl game. ... The Raptors didn't increase security Sunday. ... Toronto's Jalen Rose bruised his left thigh in the first quarter. He didn't play in the fourth.
